{
  "response_text": "The cumulative number of births remains at zero across all simulation runs for an initial duration of approximately 750 to 800 steps. Subsequently, the metric increases in discrete, stepwise increments, with final values ranging from 0 to 10 births across different simulation replicates by the end of the observation period at approximately step 2000.\n\nMost simulations recording births exhibit initial increases between steps 750 and 800, with subsequent increments clustering around steps 1000-1100 and steps 1500-1600. The intervals between these clusters approximate 730 steps, consistent with the birth-spacing parameter of 730 steps (2 years). Individual runs display extended plateaus at constant values, including stops at 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8, 9, and 10 births, with these plateaus persisting for several hundred steps before additional increases occur or the run terminates.\n\nSeveral runs accumulate births rapidly in the initial reproductive wave around step 800, reaching values of 5 or 8 births, while others show more gradual accumulation across the three main time clusters. The maximum observed value of 10 births is reached around step 1550 in one replicate, which maintains this level through step 1700. Some runs show no reproductive activity throughout the entire observation period, remaining at zero through step 1500, while others plateau at intermediate values such as 2 or 3 births and maintain these levels for the remainder of the simulation.\n\nThe discrete stepwise pattern reflects the enforcement of minimum birth-spacing intervals, while the 750-800 step delay before the first observed births corresponds to the time required for initial maturation or completion of the first interbirth interval. The variation in final cumulative births from 0 to 10 across replicates indicates stochastic differences in herd survival and reproductive success under the modeled hunting pressure and environmental conditions."
}

